  81→    </div>\n    82→  </div>\n    83→\n    84→  <script th:src=\"@{/webjars/bootstrap/dist/js/bootstrap.bundle.min.js}\"></script>\n    85→\n    86→</body>\n    87→\n    88→</html>\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"d1bfca6e-e423-4132-a6e2-418ea88669ae","uuid":"f4001e62-a90e-4475-b3ed-2c51f5670299"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_bdrk_01Kbqbno7D8PVv4BK3adPXoJ","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"I now have a thorough understanding of the codebase. This is a Spring Boot PetClinic application using Spring MVC with Thymeleaf, Spring Data JPA, H2 database, and caching. Let me now plan and execute the migration.\n\nThe key challenge here is that this is a **Thymeleaf-based MVC application** (not a REST API). For Quarkus, I'll use the Quarkus Spring compatibility extensions which provide excellent support for Spring annotations, making the migration much smoother. This approach is the most commonly adopted pattern in Quarkus for migrating Spring apps.\n\nLet me update my todo list and start working:"}],"stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":4698,"cache_read_input_tokens":59228,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":4698,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":539},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"d1bfca6e-e423-4132-a6e2-418ea88669ae","uuid":"075d6f7f-9b81-42c0-a5a5-698dc3795d14"}
