{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_bdrk_019HN8tCx5KFeqL4b9p7G6G7","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Now let me also check if there's a potential issue with `pet_count` in the ownersList template - in Qute, the implicit loop variable for checking if it's not the first item is `{pet_hasNext}` or we use `{pet_count}` but that gives the total count. Let me also check the Qute loop variable syntax. In Qute, `{pet_count}` gives the total iteration count which starts at 1. To add a comma separator, we should use `{#if pet_count > 1}` which would be `true` for the 2nd+ pet... wait, actually `pet_count` is the 1-based index of the current iteration, not the total. Let me reconsider - in Qute the implicit variable `{item_count}` gives the 1-based index. So the first pet has `pet_count == 1`, the second has `pet_count == 2`, etc. The template uses `{#if pet_count > 1}, {/if}{pet.name}` which means \"add comma before name if not the first pet\" - that's correct.\n\nNow let me also check if there are other issues. Let me look at the `error.html` template - it uses `{message ?: 'An unexpected error occurred'}` which should be fine since `?:` operator in Qute handles null/missing values. But wait, that's different from the `??` operator. In Qute, the `?:` (elvis operator) handles null values but the key still needs to be in the data map. The `??` operator checks if the key exists at all. Let me check if `message` could be missing from the data map for error.html.\n\nLet me check the CrashResource and any error handler:"}],"stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":3733,"cache_read_input_tokens":53971,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":3733,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":548},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"d1bfca6e-e423-4132-a6e2-418ea88669ae","uuid":"a12fcea2-004e-485f-87f8-3e61a13bec40"}
